/* casestudies.js — case studies 1–11 (attempt-first; model solutions render after learner attempt) */
(function (D) {
  'use strict';
  D.caseStudies = (D.caseStudies || []).concat([

  { id: 'cs1', title: 'URL-Shortening Service', difficulty: 'Beginner', banking: false,
    problem: `Design a URL-shortening service (short.co/abc123 → long URL). It must support custom aliases, link expiry, and click statistics. This is the classic warm-up — the value is in method: clarify, estimate, then design.`,
    clarifying: ['Write volume vs redirect volume (the ratio drives everything)?', 'Are analytics real-time or eventually consistent?', 'Custom alias collision policy?', 'Link lifetime — default expiry? deletion?', 'Latency target for redirects?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** create short link (optionally custom alias, expiry), redirect, click stats per link, delete/expire.\n**Non-functional:** redirect p99 < 50 ms; 99.9% availability on redirects (creation may degrade first); stats may lag minutes.\n**Constraints/assumptions:** single region initially; abuse controls (rate limits, malware scanning) in scope as a stated assumption.`,
    scale: `Assume 10M new links/month (~4/s), redirects 100:1 → ~400/s average, peak 5× → 2,000/s. Storage: 10M × ~500 B ≈ 5 GB/month raw — storage is trivial; **the redirect read path is the product**.`,
    options: `1. Single relational DB + app servers: simplest; redirect latency depends on cache hit anyway.\n2. Relational system-of-record + Redis cache-aside for redirects + async click events: the sweet spot.\n3. Fully NoSQL (key-value only): scales furthest, loses ad-hoc queries/constraints for marginal benefit at this volume.`,
    recommended: `Option 2. **Key generation:** pre-generated key pool or counter+base62 (collision-free by construction) rather than hashing-and-checking; custom aliases via unique constraint with clean 409s. **Redirect path:** cache-aside Redis (hot links are extremely skewed), TTL + explicit invalidation on delete/expiry; DB fallback on miss. **Clicks:** redirect emits an async event (queue/Kafka); an aggregator builds stats — never a synchronous DB write on the hot path.`,
    diagram: { w: 700, h: 230, boxes: [ { id: 'u', x: 20, y: 90, w: 90, label: 'Client', kind: 'user' }, { id: 'a', x: 160, y: 90, label: 'API / Redirect' }, { id: 'r', x: 340, y: 20, w: 110, label: 'Redis', kind: 'db' }, { id: 'd', x: 340, y: 150, w: 110, label: 'PostgreSQL', kind: 'db' }, { id: 'k', x: 520, y: 90, w: 110, label: 'Click events', kind: 'queue' } ], arrows: [ { from: 'u', to: 'a', label: 'GET /abc123' }, { from: 'a', to: 'r', label: 'cache' }, { from: 'a', to: 'd', label: 'miss' }, { from: 'a', to: 'k', dashed: true, label: 'async' } ] },
    tradeoffs: `Cache-aside accepts a stale window on deletions (mitigate: short TTL + invalidation). Async stats trade real-time accuracy for hot-path latency — stated and accepted. Counter-based keys need a coordination-free allocator (ranged blocks per instance) — chosen over hash collisions.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: Link(id, key, targetUrl, ownerId, expiry, createdAt), ClickAgg(linkId, day, count). APIs: POST /links (Idempotency-Key), GET /{key} (redirect), GET /links/{id}/stats, DELETE /links/{id}.`,
    kafka: `clicks.v1 keyed by linkId (per-link aggregation locality); consumer aggregates into ClickAgg; loss tolerance: at-least-once + idempotent daily upsert.`,
    security: `Rate limits per API key; malware/phishing URL scanning at creation and via nightly re-scan list; no open redirect patterns; stats endpoints auth-scoped to owners.`,
    failures: `Cache down → redirects degrade to DB (slower, alive) — verify pool sizing for that mode. Hot link (viral) → cache absorbs; guard stampede with request coalescing. Click pipeline down → redirects unaffected (the decoupling's whole point); events buffer.`,
    operations: `SLIs: redirect p99, error rate, cache hit ratio (>95% expected). Cost: tiny — one DB, small cache, few app instances; the design deliberately resists overengineering.`,
    migration: `Greenfield. Rollback = deploy rollback; schema changes expand/contract.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: counter+base62 over hashing (no collision path). ADR-2: cache-aside over write-through (staleness tolerance exists; simpler). ADR-3: async click events over sync writes (hot-path protection).`,
    followups: ['How do you handle a link going viral (hot key) beyond the cache?', 'Multi-region: where does the counter live?', 'How would you add safe-browsing checks without hurting p99?'],
    rubric: ['Clarified ratio and volumes before designing', 'Read path optimised with explicit staleness handling', 'Key generation collision-free by construction', 'Async stats with loss/duplication semantics stated', 'Resisted overengineering'] },

  { id: 'cs2', title: 'Online Bookstore', difficulty: 'Beginner', banking: false,
    problem: `Design the backend for an online bookstore: catalogue browsing/search, cart, orders, payments (via a PSP), inventory, reviews. A deliberate exercise in NOT using microservices prematurely.`,
    clarifying: ['Traffic and catalogue size?', 'One team or several?', 'Physical inventory or also e-books?', 'Payment: full PCI scope or PSP-tokenised?', 'Search sophistication needed?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** browse/search catalogue, cart, checkout with PSP payment, order tracking, inventory decrement, reviews.\n**NFR:** browse p95 < 300 ms; checkout availability 99.9%; order-payment consistency (no paid-but-lost orders); search freshness minutes.\n**Assumptions:** one team of 6; 50k DAU; PSP handles card data (tokenised — we stay out of PCI scope).`,
    scale: `50k DAU × 20 requests ≈ 1M req/day ≈ 12/s avg, 60/s peak. 500k catalogue items. Orders ~2k/day. These numbers justify **one well-structured deployable**.`,
    options: `1. Modular monolith + PostgreSQL + Elasticsearch for search: fits team and load.\n2. Microservices per domain: pays the premium with no team-scale driver.\n3. Monolith without module discipline: cheap now, the classic ball of mud later.`,
    recommended: `Modular monolith (catalogue, ordering, inventory, review modules with enforced boundaries — schema-per-module, ArchUnit rules), PostgreSQL as SoR, Elasticsearch as a rebuildable search read model fed by catalogue events (in-process bus → outbox if extracted later). Checkout is the one flow engineered hard: idempotent order creation, PSP webhook handling with signature verification and dedupe, order state machine (CREATED→PAYMENT_PENDING→PAID→FULFILLING…), inventory reservation with expiring holds.`,
    tradeoffs: `Monolith trades independent scaling (not needed) for transactional simplicity — order+inventory+payment-state in one ACID transaction avoids a saga entirely at this scale. ES adds an ops dependency for real search value; freshness lag accepted and displayed.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: Book, Inventory(bookId, onHand, reserved), Cart, Order(+items, state), Payment(pspRef, state), Review. APIs: /catalogue (search, detail), /cart, POST /orders (Idempotency-Key), /orders/{id}, PSP webhook endpoint.`,
    kafka: `Not yet — an in-process event bus with the same event shapes (OrderPaid, StockChanged) keeps the extraction path open. The ADR records the trigger for real Kafka: a second consumer team.`,
    security: `PSP tokenisation keeps card data out; OIDC login; webhook signature validation + replay dedupe; review-spam rate limiting; PII (addresses) classified and masked in non-prod.`,
    failures: `PSP down → orders park in PAYMENT_PENDING with retry + user messaging; never double-charge (idempotency key per payment attempt). ES down → degraded catalogue browse by category from DB (designed degraded mode). Inventory race on last copy → reservation with unique constraint decides; loser gets a clean out-of-stock.`,
    operations: `SLIs per journey (browse, checkout success rate). Single deployable = simple on-call. Load test at 5× before marketing events.`,
    migration: `Greenfield; the module boundaries ARE the migration plan for the day team #2 arrives.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: modular monolith over microservices (team size, load — with extraction triggers). ADR-2: reservation-with-expiry over decrement-at-order (oversell prevention vs abandoned-cart lockup). ADR-3: ES as derived read model, never SoR.`,
    followups: ['Team grows to three teams — which module extracts first and why?', 'Add e-books: what changes in inventory and fulfilment?', 'Black-Friday: which parts of cs3\'s checkout hardening apply here?'],
    rubric: ['Justified the monolith from team+load facts', 'Checkout consistency engineered (idempotency, webhook dedupe, state machine)', 'Search as rebuildable derived store', 'Degraded modes designed', 'Extraction path preserved'] },

  { id: 'cs3', title: 'E-Commerce Checkout at Black-Friday Scale', difficulty: 'Intermediate', banking: false,
    problem: `Design a checkout flow that survives Black Friday: 50× normal traffic for 6 hours, flash-sale items with limited stock, and a payment provider that WILL wobble under load. No overselling, no double-charging, graceful behaviour at saturation.`,
    clarifying: ['Peak checkout attempts/s and the conversion funnel shape?', 'Oversell tolerance — strictly zero or business-accepted 0.x%?', 'Multiple PSPs available for failover?', 'Can browsing degrade to protect checkout?', 'Queue/waiting-room acceptable to the business?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** cart → reserve stock → pay → confirm; flash-sale fairness; order status visibility.\n**NFR:** zero oversell on flash items; zero double-charge; checkout p99 < 3 s at 5,000 attempts/s peak; the system sheds gracefully past capacity (waiting room), never collapses.\n**Constraints:** PSP rate limit 2,000 tx/s contracted; 6-week runway.`,
    scale: `5,000 checkout attempts/s peak; 60% funnel to payment → 3,000 payments/s desired vs PSP's 2,000/s → **the maths forces a queue/waiting-room decision up front** — this is the case study's core lesson: arithmetic drives architecture.`,
    options: `1. Scale everything ×50 synchronously: PSP limit makes this arithmetically impossible.\n2. Async order pipeline with reservation + queued payment: matches the PSP constraint.\n3. Waiting room ahead of checkout + option 2: adds fairness and protects the whole funnel.`,
    recommended: `Option 3. **Waiting room** (token bucket admission at sustainable rate) → **reservation service** (atomic decrement with expiring holds — Redis with Lua or DB row-level, sized for the flash SKUs' contention) → **payment orchestrator** consuming a queue at PSP-safe rate with idempotency keys per order → confirmation events → async everything else (email, loyalty, analytics). Browsing serves from CDN/cache aggressively and degrades first by design.`,
    tradeoffs: `Customers queue visibly instead of experiencing random failures — a business-approved honesty trade. Reservation holds trade stock liquidity (held-but-abandoned) against oversell; expiry tuning (e.g. 10 min) is a product decision. The async pipeline means confirmation is seconds later — communicated in UX.`,
    dataApis: `Order state machine: DRAFT→RESERVED→PAYMENT_QUEUED→PAID|PAYMENT_FAILED(→re-queue|release)→CONFIRMED. POST /checkout (Idempotency-Key), GET /orders/{id} (status polling/push).`,
    kafka: `orders.events.v1 keyed by orderId; payment-requests queue consumed at governed rate (competing consumers ≤ PSP budget); DLT for poison orders with ops alerting; click/analytics fan-out isolated from the money path.`,
    security: `Bot defence at the waiting room (the scalpers arrive first); PSP webhook signature + dedupe; rate limits per account; fraud scoring async post-auth for this volume tier with post-hoc capture policies.`,
    failures: `PSP browns out → queue absorbs, drain rate adapts to error rate (adaptive concurrency), orders age visibly, business-approved max-wait then auto-release + apologise. Reservation store fails → checkout closes cleanly (waiting room holds), browse unaffected. Double-submit storms → idempotency keys make them no-ops.`,
    operations: `War-room dashboards: admission rate, reservation contention, PSP error/latency, queue depth vs drain, oversell counter (must read 0). Load-tested at 1.5× projected peak with the real funnel shape. Feature flags arm the waiting room and degradation tiers.`,
    migration: `Built beside the normal checkout; traffic switched by flag at campaign start; rollback = flag off (normal path retained).`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: waiting room over overprovisioning (PSP contract makes overprovisioning useless). ADR-2: reservation-with-expiry over optimistic oversell-and-refund (brand damage priced). ADR-3: async confirmation accepted (UX honesty over fake synchrony).`,
    followups: ['Where exactly can this design still oversell, however unlikely?', 'PSP-2 failover mid-sale: what breaks?', 'How would you test the waiting-room fairness claim?'],
    rubric: ['PSP arithmetic drove the design', 'Reservation semantics precise (holds, expiry, contention)', 'Idempotency end-to-end on money', 'Designed degradation ladder with business sign-off', 'Async boundaries protect the paid path'] },

  { id: 'cs4', title: 'Notification Platform', difficulty: 'Intermediate', banking: false,
    problem: `Build the company-wide notification platform (email, SMS, push, in-app) consumed by 20+ producer teams. Today every team integrates providers directly — credential sprawl, no preferences, no evidence, and last month a provider outage broke checkout (see review scenario rv8).`,
    clarifying: ['Regulatory notices in scope (evidence requirements)?', 'Volume per channel and peak shape?', 'Consent/preference source of truth today?', 'Latency tiers — OTP vs marketing?', 'Template ownership model?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** accept notification requests via events/API; template rendering (multi-language); preference/consent enforcement; provider routing with failover; delivery tracking; quiet hours; digest bundling.\n**NFR:** OTP p99 < 5 s end-to-end; marketing may lag minutes; regulatory notices with delivery evidence retained 7 years; platform outage must NEVER block producers (fire-and-forget contract).\n**Volumes:** 5M/day, OTP 50k/day, peak 500/s (marketing bursts).`,
    scale: `500/s peak ingest is modest for a log-based pipeline; the interesting sizing is per-provider rate limits (e.g. SMS 100/s contracted) → priority queues per channel with governed drain rates.`,
    options: `1. Shared library per team: fixes nothing structural (credentials, preferences still scattered).\n2. Central synchronous API: creates the checkout-breaking coupling again.\n3. Event-driven central platform: producers publish and forget; the platform owns delivery.`,
    recommended: `Option 3. Producers publish NotificationRequested (versioned contract, idempotency key = producer+businessRef) to notifications.requests.v1; the platform validates, checks **consent/preferences centrally**, renders templates, routes to provider adapters via **priority lanes** (OTP lane drains first, marketing throttles), tracks per-notification state (REQUESTED→RENDERED→SENT→DELIVERED|FAILED→retries→DLT), and emits status events producers may consume. Regulatory notices ride a dedicated lane with delivery-evidence capture and an escalation channel on failure.`,
    tradeoffs: `Producers lose direct control (a team wanting a bespoke provider negotiates with the platform — a governance cost accepted for the credential/consent/evidence wins). Fire-and-forget means producers must design for "requested ≠ delivered" — status events exist for those who care.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: NotificationRequest, Template(version, locale), Preference/Consent, DeliveryAttempt, ProviderAccount. APIs: POST /notifications (for non-event producers), GET /notifications/{id}, template CRUD (governed), preference APIs.`,
    kafka: `requests.v1 keyed by recipientId (per-recipient ordering enables digest/quiet-hour logic); priority via separate lane topics per channel+tier; status.v1 keyed likewise; DLTs per lane with alerting; retention 7d except evidence sink (separate immutable store).`,
    security: `Central vault-issued provider credentials (rotation finally possible); template injection defences (no raw producer HTML into email); PII minimisation in events (recipientId + template vars, classified); consent enforcement is a **control**, logged.`,
    failures: `Provider outage → adapter breaker opens, failover to secondary where contracted, else queue and drain (OTP failover mandatory — OTPs can't wait); platform DB down → ingest continues (Kafka buffers), processing resumes — producers unaffected (the whole point); duplicate requests → idempotency key dedupe; template bug → per-template kill switch, DLT replay after fix.`,
    operations: `SLIs per tier (OTP p99 end-to-end is the flagship); per-provider health dashboards; queue-age alerting per lane; cost per channel tracked (SMS spend is real money).`,
    migration: `Strangle team by team: platform shadows an existing team's sends first (compare), then cuts over; nine direct provider accounts retired one by one; the checkout coupling removed in wave one by contract.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: events over sync API as the producer contract (outage isolation). ADR-2: central consent enforcement (one control point vs 20 hopeful implementations). ADR-3: per-recipient event key (ordering enables digests/quiet hours; accepted hot-recipient risk negligible).`,
    followups: ['An OTP is 30 s late — walk the diagnosis path through your design.', 'How does the platform prove a regulatory notice was delivered?', 'A producer wants WhatsApp — what changes?'],
    rubric: ['Producer isolation (fire-and-forget) achieved', 'Priority lanes with per-provider rate governance', 'Consent as enforced control', 'Evidence path for regulatory notices', 'Migration strangles rather than big-bangs'] },

  { id: 'cs5', title: 'File-Processing Platform', difficulty: 'Intermediate', banking: false,
    problem: `Design a platform ingesting thousands of files daily (CSV, XML, fixed-width; KB to 10 GB) from hundreds of external parties, each with format quirks, SLAs, and re-send habits. Downstream systems need validated, normalised records with full lineage.`,
    clarifying: ['Formats per sender governed by contracts?', 'Partial-failure policy: reject file or reject records?', 'SLA shape — cut-off driven?', 'Duplicate file frequency and detection expectations?', 'Peak concurrency (month-end)?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** secure intake (SFTP/API/object drop), integrity verification, duplicate detection, format-specific parsing, validation, normalisation, routing to consumers, per-file and per-record status, replay.\n**NFR:** 4-hour SLA per file class with cut-off alerting; a 10 GB file must not starve small files; lineage: any output record traceable to file+line; poison files quarantined never lost.`,
    scale: `~5k files/day, 50M records/day, month-end 4×. The 10 GB outliers force streaming parsers and per-stage scaling — the platform is pipes-and-filters by nature.`,
    options: `1. Monolithic parser service: one bad 10 GB file blocks the world.\n2. Pipes-and-filters with per-stage queues: independent scaling and failure isolation per stage.\n3. Fully serverless per file: elegant for small files, execution limits fight the 10 GB reality.`,
    recommended: `Option 2. Landing (object storage; checksum + completeness marker before visibility) → **intake registrar** (file identity, duplicate hash check, metadata record — the file's lifecycle anchor) → format-specific **parser workers** (streaming, sender-config-driven) → **validation/normalisation** stages → routed record streams for consumers + rejects with reasons. Every stage: queue-fed, horizontally scaled, poison-quarantine path. A **file-status service** aggregates stage events into the per-file view operations lives in ("will BATCH-4711 make the 16:00 cut-off?").`,
    tradeoffs: `Per-stage queues add latency (minutes — fine vs the 4 h SLA) and moving parts, buying isolation: the 10 GB monster occupies big-file workers while small files flow. Record-level rejection policy is contractual per sender — the platform supports both, defaulting to record-reject with a file-reject threshold (>5% errors = probably a wrong file).`,
    dataApis: `Entities: FileRegistration, SenderConfig(format, policy, SLA), StageEvent, RecordLineage(recordId→fileId+line), Reject. APIs: sender status portal, ops dashboards, replay endpoints.`,
    kafka: `Stage topics keyed by fileId (per-file stage ordering); record streams keyed by business key for consumers; claim-check pattern throughout (payloads in object storage, events carry references) — 10 GB never transits Kafka.`,
    security: `Per-sender credentials/allowlists; malware scanning at landing; parser sandboxing (parsers are attack surface — malformed input is hostile input); PII classification per feed driving masking in rejects/logs.`,
    failures: `Truncated upload → completeness marker absent, never processed, sender notified. Duplicate file → hash match, registrar links to original, policy decides (ignore/replace/alert). Mid-file crash → stage checkpointing by record offset; idempotent record emission (fileId+line keys). Poison file → quarantine + alert + sender feedback loop; replay after parser fix re-runs from landing (immutable original retained).`,
    operations: `The cut-off dashboard is the product for ops: per-file ETA vs SLA with amber/red. Month-end capacity pre-scaled by calendar. Cost: object storage lifecycle (originals 90 d hot, archive per retention contract).`,
    migration: `Sender-by-sender migration from the legacy scripts; parallel-run compares outputs per sender before cutover; the legacy NFS mount retires last.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: pipes-and-filters over monolith (isolation, per-stage scale). ADR-2: claim-check with object storage (10 GB reality). ADR-3: record-level lineage as a first-class store (regulated consumers demanded it; cost accepted).`,
    followups: ['A sender re-sends yesterday\'s file with 3 changed records — behaviour?', 'Where does backpressure appear when consumers slow down?', 'How would you add a real-time (streaming) sender to this batch-shaped platform?'],
    rubric: ['Integrity-before-visibility intake', 'Streaming + claim-check for the size outliers', 'Per-stage isolation with poison paths', 'Lineage and per-file status as products', 'Duplicate-file policy explicit'] },

  { id: 'cs6', title: 'Video-Streaming Service', difficulty: 'Intermediate', banking: false,
    problem: `Design video streaming for a mid-size platform: creators upload; viewers stream on web/mobile; adaptive quality; view counts and watch-time analytics. Not Netflix scale — 100k concurrent viewers peak — which makes the trade-offs more interesting, not less.`,
    clarifying: ['Live streaming in scope or VOD only?', 'DRM requirements?', 'Upload sizes and transcoding turnaround expectations?', 'Own CDN vs commercial?', 'Analytics precision (billing-grade or trend-grade)?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** upload → transcode (multi-bitrate HLS/DASH) → publish; adaptive streaming; resume position; view/watch-time analytics; basic recommendations.\n**NFR:** time-to-first-frame p95 < 1.5 s; 99.9% playback availability; transcode turnaround < 30 min for 1 h video; analytics trend-grade (±1% fine).\n**Assumptions:** VOD only; commercial CDN; DRM out of scope v1 (stated!).`,
    scale: `100k concurrent × ~4 Mbps ≈ 400 Gbps peak egress — **CDN is not optional, it IS the delivery architecture**; origin serves only cache misses. Uploads 5k/day × avg 2 GB = 10 TB/day into transcoding: a queue-fed farm, spot/preemptible-friendly (interruptible batch).`,
    options: `1. Serve from own origin + cache: 400 Gbps says no.\n2. Commercial CDN + object-storage origin + transcode farm: the standard shape, for standard reasons.\n3. Full managed video platform (buy): legitimate — scored in the ADR; build chosen here for cost-at-scale and control (the case study assumes that analysis).`,
    recommended: `Upload service (resumable/multipart to object storage) → transcode pipeline (queue → containerised ffmpeg workers, spot instances, per-rendition jobs fan-out/fan-in) → packaged HLS/DASH renditions in origin buckets → CDN with signed URLs. Playback API issues manifests + tokens; **client-side adaptive** bitrate (that's the protocol's job). Analytics: client beacons → gateway → Kafka → streaming aggregation (view counts, watch time) with trend-grade sampling honesty.`,
    tradeoffs: `Commercial CDN trades egress cost for capex/ops it would take years to match — revisit at sustained multi-Tbps only. Spot-instance transcoding trades occasional restarts (checkpoint per rendition) for ~70% compute savings. Trend-grade analytics (sampled, eventually consistent) traded against billing-grade cost — stated because someone WILL later ask for creator payouts (that becomes billing-grade: exact, audited — a new requirement, new design).`,
    dataApis: `Entities: Video(id, owner, status), Rendition, PlaybackSession, ViewAgg. APIs: upload (resumable), GET /videos/{id}/manifest (tokened), progress beacons, creator stats.`,
    kafka: `playback.beacons.v1 keyed by sessionId (high volume, loss-tolerant — at-most-once acceptable and stated); transcode.jobs queue semantics; video.lifecycle.v1 for catalogue/search consumers.`,
    security: `Signed, expiring CDN URLs (hotlink defence); upload malware scanning; creator authZ on stats; beacon endpoints rate-limited (they're a DDoS magnet).`,
    failures: `Transcode worker dies mid-job → rendition-level retry (idempotent: same input → same output path). CDN regional issue → multi-CDN or origin-shield fallback with degraded quality cap. Analytics pipeline down → playback unaffected (beacons drop — the stated at-most-once trade). Popular video thundering-herd on publish → CDN pre-warm on publish event.`,
    operations: `SLIs: time-to-first-frame, rebuffer ratio, transcode queue age. Cost is dominated by egress + storage: rendition lifecycle policies (rarely-watched → cheaper tiers, re-transcode-on-demand debate recorded in ADR).`,
    migration: `Greenfield-ish; the buy-vs-build ADR is the migration insurance (managed platform remains the fallback).`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: commercial CDN (egress arithmetic). ADR-2: spot transcoding with checkpoints (cost vs restart complexity). ADR-3: at-most-once beacons (volume vs trend-grade need — revisited if payouts arrive).`,
    followups: ['Creator payouts arrive: what must change in analytics?', 'Add live streaming: which components survive?', 'A copyright-strike workflow — where does it attach?'],
    rubric: ['Egress arithmetic drove CDN decision', 'Transcode pipeline idempotent and interruption-tolerant', 'Analytics precision honestly tiered', 'Failure modes per component with playback protected', 'Buy option genuinely considered'] },

  { id: 'cs7', title: 'Ride-Hailing Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: false,
    problem: `Design the core of a ride-hailing service for one large city: riders request, nearby drivers matched, live tracking, dynamic pricing, trip settlement. Real-time state at scale with money attached.`,
    clarifying: ['City scale: drivers online, requests/s at Friday peak?', 'Matching latency target?', 'Surge pricing rules owned by whom?', 'Offline/poor-network behaviour for drivers?', 'Settlement: instant or batched to drivers?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** driver presence/location, ride request → match → accept → track → complete → charge → settle; surge pricing; cancellation flows both sides.\n**NFR:** match p95 < 3 s; location updates 1–4 s fresh; platform 99.95% during peaks; no double-charge, no lost trips; pricing auditable (disputes).\n**Scale:** 50k concurrent drivers, 500 requests/s peak, 12k location updates/s.`,
    scale: `Location stream dominates: 12k/s updates → geo-indexed in-memory state (this is THE stateful component); trips ~500/s peak create modest transactional load; the asymmetry (heavy ephemeral vs light durable) shapes everything.`,
    options: `1. Everything in one DB: location write volume + geo queries kill it.\n2. In-memory geo index (Redis GEO/custom cells) for presence + durable trip store: the standard split.\n3. Full event-sourced everything: trip state benefits; location history doesn't need it (retention!).`,
    recommended: `**Presence service**: driver locations into geo-sharded in-memory store (city cells; hot-cell aware), TTL-expired (a silent driver vanishes from matching — safety by default). **Matching**: request → candidate query by cell ring → ranking (ETA, rating) → offer/accept state machine with timeout cascade to next candidate; idempotent accept (two taps ≠ two trips). **Trip service**: durable state machine (REQUESTED→MATCHED→ENROUTE→ACTIVE→COMPLETED→CHARGED), event-sourced for dispute-grade history. **Pricing**: surge computed per cell from supply/demand streams, versioned quotes locked at request time (the quote the rider saw is the quote charged — auditability). **Settlement**: charge via PSP (idempotency keys), driver payouts batched daily.`,
    tradeoffs: `In-memory presence trades durability (a restart forgets locations — drivers re-ping within seconds, acceptable and stated) for the only viable latency. Locked quotes trade surge responsiveness for dispute defensibility — a regulator-shaped choice. Cell sharding trades cross-cell boundary matching complexity for horizontal scale.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: DriverPresence(ephemeral), Trip(event-sourced), Quote(versioned), Charge, Payout. APIs: driver location ping, POST /rides (Idempotency-Key), offer accept/decline, trip tracking (push), receipt/dispute.`,
    kafka: `locations.v1 keyed by driverId (per-driver order; short retention — hours); trips.events.v1 keyed by tripId (the audit spine); pricing.cells.v1 compacted (latest surge per cell); settlement events to payment consumers.`,
    security: `Driver identity verification; location data = sensitive personal data (retention minimised, access audited — insider stalking is a real threat model entry); PSP tokenised payments; anti-fraud on GPS spoofing (impossible-speed detection).`,
    failures: `Presence node lost → cell re-pings repopulate in seconds; matching degrades briefly (widened rings). PSP down at trip end → trip completes, charge queues with retry (driver paid on schedule regardless — trust asymmetry decision). Offer timeout storms Friday night → timeout cascade tuned, and surge is the systemic backpressure. Network-poor driver → client-side buffering, server tolerance windows, trip state reconstruction from both phones' logs on dispute.`,
    operations: `Peak-shaped capacity (Friday 8pm is the design point); match-rate and time-to-match SLIs per cell; surge-vs-supply dashboards; chaos drills on presence-node loss.`,
    migration: `City-by-city rollout IS the migration strategy; each city a capacity cell with local tuning.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: ephemeral in-memory presence (latency vs durability — re-ping makes durability unnecessary). ADR-2: event-sourced trips (dispute evidence). ADR-3: locked quotes (auditability over surge purity).`,
    followups: ['Two riders, one driver, simultaneous accepts — walk the race.', 'How does the design cap the blast radius of a bad pricing deploy?', 'Cross-city trips: what breaks in cell sharding?'],
    rubric: ['Ephemeral/durable split reasoned from data physics', 'Matching race conditions handled (idempotent accept, timeout cascade)', 'Money path idempotent with dispute-grade evidence', 'Location privacy treated as a threat model entry', 'Peak-shaped capacity thinking'] },

  { id: 'cs8', title: 'Multi-Tenant SaaS Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: false,
    problem: `Design a B2B SaaS platform (compliance-workflow software sold to banks, pleasingly recursive) serving 500 tenants from 10-seat startups to 10k-seat institutions. Tenants demand isolation guarantees, some demand residency, the big ones demand dedicated instances — and the unit economics must still work.`,
    clarifying: ['Isolation spectrum tenants actually require (contractual vs assumed)?', 'Residency jurisdictions in scope?', 'Per-tenant customisation depth (config vs code)?', 'Noisy-neighbour SLAs?', 'Tenant offboarding/data-export obligations?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** tenant onboarding/offboarding, per-tenant config + branding, RBAC per tenant, usage metering, tenant-scoped everything.\n**NFR:** hard data isolation (a cross-tenant leak is existential); per-tenant restore ("restore tenant 42 to yesterday"); noisy-neighbour caps; 99.9% standard tier, 99.95% enterprise; unit cost per tenant-seat tracked.\n**Constraints:** EU + CH residency demanded by 20% of revenue; 3 enterprise tenants demand dedicated stacks.`,
    scale: `500 tenants, ~100k total seats, wildly skewed (top 10 tenants = 60% of load) — the skew IS the architecture problem: pooled economics for the long tail, isolation options for the whales.`,
    options: `1. Shared-everything (tenant_id column): best economics, weakest isolation, per-tenant restore is surgery.\n2. Tiered: pooled (schema-per-tenant) standard + dedicated stacks enterprise: matches the revenue shape.\n3. Dedicated-everything: economics fail for the 10-seat tail.`,
    recommended: `Option 2 — **tiered tenancy as a product feature**: standard tier on pooled clusters with schema-per-tenant (real isolation boundary, per-tenant backup/restore, migration tooling per schema), enterprise tier as dedicated stack from the same IaC modules (one codebase, N deployments), residency via regional pooled clusters (EU, CH cells). Tenancy context flows in a signed claim through every call; **every** query is tenant-scoped by construction (repository layer enforces — no raw table access); per-tenant quotas/rate limits cap noisy neighbours; metering events feed billing and unit-cost dashboards.`,
    tradeoffs: `Schema-per-tenant trades migration fan-out (500 schemas × every migration — invest in automation) for restore/isolation wins. Tiering trades operational variety (pooled + dedicated) for revenue fit. The repository-enforced scoping trades a little developer freedom for the property that cross-tenant leakage requires *deliberate* effort — the right direction for existential risks.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: Tenant(tier, region, config), TenantUser, Entitlement, UsageEvent. Control-plane APIs (onboard, configure, export, offboard) separated from data-plane APIs (the product itself). Export: full tenant data in documented format — contractual, tested (the SaaS-exit lesson applied to ourselves).`,
    kafka: `Per-region clusters; topics tenant-scoped by key (tenantId) with quotas; control-plane events (TenantProvisioned, TierChanged); metering stream to billing. Dedicated stacks get their own everything — no cross-tenant broker sharing at enterprise tier.`,
    security: `Tenant isolation is threat-model priority one: signed tenant claims, repository-layer scoping, per-tenant encryption keys (crypto-shreds on offboarding!), quarterly cross-tenant-leak pentesting, per-tenant audit trails (their regulators ask them, they ask us).`,
    failures: `Pooled-cluster incident → blast radius = that cell's tenants (cells sized to cap it); noisy neighbour → quotas throttle with tenant-visible messaging; bad migration → per-schema rollout (canary tenants first!) makes it a partial, reversible event; tenant offboarding → export, crypto-shred, evidence of deletion (their compliance needs it).`,
    operations: `Per-tenant health/SLO views (enterprise tenants see theirs); migration automation as a first-class product; cost per tenant per month monitored — the tail must stay profitable.`,
    migration: `Existing single-tenant customers migrate tenant-by-tenant into cells; the dedicated-stack IaC is the escape valve for the ones who refuse.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: tiered tenancy over one-size (revenue shape). ADR-2: schema-per-tenant on the pooled tier (restore + isolation vs migration fan-out). ADR-3: per-tenant encryption keys (offboarding proof + breach containment).`,
    followups: ['Tenant 7 demands their data never leaves Switzerland including backups — walk the design response.', 'A migration corrupts 30 schemas before the canary alarm — recover.', 'Where does per-tenant customisation stop being config and start being a fork?'],
    rubric: ['Tiering derived from tenant/revenue skew', 'Isolation enforced structurally, not by convention', 'Per-tenant restore and offboarding designed', 'Noisy-neighbour and unit-economics instrumentation', 'Residency as cells, not filters'] },

  { id: 'cs9', title: 'Banking Payment Platform (flagship)', difficulty: 'Expert', banking: true,
    problem: `Design the bank's payment platform: SEPA batch + instant payments, 5M payments/day, peak 400/s, 99.95% submission availability, full duplicate defence, scheme reconciliation, and a board that remembers last year's duplicate-payment incident. The b4/lab-28 material as one coherent design.`,
    clarifying: ['Rails in scope (SEPA CT, instant, international later)?', 'Core banking posting: real-time or windowed?', 'Existing fraud/screening services to integrate or build?', 'Cut-off times and EOD dependencies?', 'RTO/RPO per business service?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** initiation (channels, files, APIs) → validation → fraud + sanctions checks → reservation → clearing (rail-specific) → settlement handling → posting → notifications; reversals/returns; status APIs.\n**NFR:** instant rail ≤ 10 s confirm-or-reject; submission 99.95%; zero duplicate posting (board-visible); RPO 0 on payment store; scheme reconciliation daily with 100% break workflow; evidence per payment 10 years.\n**Constraints:** core posts in windows overnight for batch; instant posts real-time to a shadow ledger reconciled to core.`,
    scale: `400/s peak (5× salary-day factor over average), instant share growing 40%/yr; sizing at 3× peak headroom, load-tested at month-end profile. Payment store growth ~1 TB/yr → date partitioning + queryable archive per retention.`,
    options: `1. Extend the batch engine for instant (review scenario rv6 shows how that dies).\n2. Separate instant spine sharing componentised checks: rails differ in physics, checks don't.\n3. Vendor payment hub: scored — loses on evidence-layer lock-in and per-tx pricing at this volume (recorded in ADR with numbers).`,
    recommended: `Option 2. **Shared components**: intake APIs (idempotency keys, correlation IDs), validation, fraud scoring (budgeted per rail), sanctions check (pre-computed party status + payment-data screening, 2 s budget on instant), reservation service (the anti-double-spend control, optimistic on account version). **Instant spine**: event-driven state machine (paymentId-keyed ordered stream, NO retry topics — sequence integrity over throughput), scheme adapter managing the 10 s deadline (timeout → status inquiry → definitive state), real-time shadow-ledger posting, core reconciliation at window. **Batch spine**: file intake (cs5 patterns), cut-off-aware scheduling, bulk optimised. **Duplicate defence in five layers**: API keys, business window (debtor+creditor+amount+ref), inbox consumers, scheme checks, daily reconciliation.`,
    diagram: { w: 720, h: 300, boxes: [ { id: 'ch', x: 10, y: 120, w: 100, label: 'Channels' }, { id: 'in', x: 150, y: 120, w: 120, label: 'Intake + Idem' }, { id: 'chk', x: 310, y: 30, w: 130, label: 'Fraud + Sanctions' }, { id: 'res', x: 310, y: 120, w: 130, label: 'Reservation' }, { id: 'inst', x: 310, y: 210, w: 130, label: 'Instant spine' }, { id: 'sch', x: 490, y: 210, w: 110, label: 'Scheme adapter', kind: 'ext' }, { id: 'led', x: 490, y: 120, w: 110, label: 'Shadow ledger', kind: 'db' }, { id: 'k', x: 490, y: 30, w: 110, label: 'payment.events', kind: 'queue' }, { id: 'rec', x: 630, y: 120, w: 80, h: 90, label: 'Recon' } ], arrows: [ { from: 'ch', to: 'in' }, { from: 'in', to: 'chk' }, { from: 'in', to: 'inst' }, { from: 'inst', to: 'res' }, { from: 'inst', to: 'sch', label: '≤10s' }, { from: 'inst', to: 'led' }, { from: 'inst', to: 'k', dashed: true }, { from: 'led', to: 'rec' }, { from: 'sch', to: 'rec', dashed: true } ] },
    tradeoffs: `Two spines cost duplicated pipeline plumbing, buying rail-appropriate semantics (block-and-alert ordering on instant; throughput lanes on batch). RPO 0 on the payment store costs synchronous standby latency — scoped to the payment store only, not analytics. Pre-computed screening status trades a bounded staleness window (list-delta events shrink it to minutes) for the 10 s budget — the staleness bound is compliance-signed.`,
    dataApis: `Payment(id, idempotencyKey, state, rail, amounts, parties-refs, versions), Reservation, LedgerEntry, ReconBreak. APIs: POST /payments (Idempotency-Key mandatory), GET /payments/{id}, status webhooks/events, reversal initiation (maker-checker above thresholds).`,
    kafka: `payment.events.v1 keyed by paymentId (state machine order; consumers: notification, fraud-feedback, audit, analytics — separate groups); transaction.events keyed by accountId for balance consumers; outbox everywhere a DB state change emits; DLT policy: instant spine = block-and-alert, peripheral consumers = retry tiers + DLT.`,
    security: `mTLS everywhere; payment repair admin plane behind PAM + four-eyes + session recording (the threat model's crown jewel); coded rejection reasons (no screening-logic leakage); log allowlists (no amounts-with-names in logs); ISO 20022 structured data improving screening precision.`,
    failures: `Scheme timeout → INQUIRING state → definitive resolution, customer never sees maybe. Core window overrun → instant continues on shadow ledger, batch queues, reconciliation extends — degradation ladder business-signed. Orchestrator DB loss → the lab-52 recovery: stop intake, restore, reconstruct from outbox events + scheme inquiries, reconcile before resume. Duplicate file from a corporate → business-window dedupe holds it for review.`,
    operations: `SLIs: submission success rate, instant confirm p99, reconciliation break count (target 0, every break worked same-day), cut-off ETA dashboards; month-end capacity rehearsed; game days quarterly incl. region failover (RTO 15 min proven, not promised).`,
    migration: `Instant spine built greenfield beside the existing batch engine; batch strangled component-by-component after (intake first, posting last); every phase parallel-run with reconciliation; the old engine's retirement is a dated milestone, not a hope.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: dual spine over unified engine (rail physics). ADR-2: five-layer duplicate defence (board mandate; each layer's coverage documented). ADR-3: shadow ledger + window reconciliation (instant vs core reality). ADR-4: RPO-0 scoped to payment store (cost honesty).`,
    followups: ['Where exactly does the design still permit a duplicate, and what is that probability story?', 'Defend the pre-computed screening status to the MLRO.', 'The scheme changes its timeout from 10 s to 5 s — what breaks first?'],
    rubric: ['Rail separation with shared checks reasoned', 'Five-layer duplicate defence complete', 'Unknown-outcome states resolved definitively', 'Shadow-ledger reconciliation designed', 'Evidence + admin-plane controls present', 'Degradation ladder business-signed'] },

  { id: 'cs10', title: 'Customer Onboarding Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Design bank-grade customer onboarding: application through identity verification, KYC, screening, risk rating, approval, account opening — target ≤ 1 day (from 5), with controls intact and every decision evidenced. Lab 11's workflow, engineered fully.`,
    clarifying: ['Which segments (retail simple vs corporate with UBO complexity)?', 'Provisional activation policy appetite?', 'Verification vendors chosen or to select?', 'Abandonment rates and resume expectations?', 'Peak application volumes (campaign-driven?)'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** multi-channel application capture with save/resume; document + identity verification (vendor); KYC data collection; screening (via the screening platform's contract); risk rating; approval workflow (four-eyes above risk thresholds); core account opening; activation.\n**NFR:** applicant-visible status always current; screening decision p99 < 5 s interactive; full evidence per decision 10 y; abandoned applications expire with retention rules; 99.9% availability business hours.\n**Volumes:** 3k applications/day, campaign peaks 15k/day.`,
    scale: `Modest transactional volume — the complexity is workflow state, vendor orchestration and evidence, not throughput. Campaign peaks stress the vendor quotas (verification vendor 50/s contracted) → queue-based pacing.`,
    options: `1. Synchronous chain from the web form (rv1's corpse).\n2. Orchestrated workflow with async vendor legs: the shape the domain demands.\n3. BPM-suite-everything: legitimate; scored — chosen engine embedded (Temporal/Camunda-style) rather than enterprise-BPM-monolith, for testability.`,
    recommended: `**Orchestrated** (explicit state machine per application: the applicant, ops and auditors all ask "where is application X"). Stages as async legs with vendor adapters (ACL + resilience + queue pacing): verification, screening (consuming the b5 platform's contract), risk rating (rules engine, versioned). **Approval**: risk-tiered — low risk straight-through (the 1-day target lives here), high risk to human four-eyes queues with SLA monitoring. **Provisional activation** where compliance signed the policy: account opens with restricted limits pending final clearance — the policy, its limits and its audit trail are explicit product features. Every stage transition: audit event with data versions; applicant status derives from orchestrator state.`,
    tradeoffs: `Orchestration centralises flow logic (the orchestrator must stay thin — stage services own their rules). Straight-through processing trades human review for speed on low-risk only — the risk-tiering model is versioned, back-tested, compliance-owned. Provisional activation trades control timing for conversion, bounded by limits — a risk decision made visible, not buried.`,
    dataApis: `Application(id, state, channel, savepoints), VerificationResult(vendor, evidence-ref), RiskRating(model-version, inputs-hash), Approval(maker, checker), plus the screening contract's entities. APIs: application CRUD with resume tokens, status, document upload (claim-check to object storage), ops worklists.`,
    kafka: `onboarding.events.v1 keyed by applicationId; consumes screening.results.v1; publishes ApplicationApproved consumed by account domain + CRM; outbox throughout; abandoned-application expiry events drive data-retention jobs.`,
    security: `Applicant data is pre-customer PII (consent + retention rules differ from customers!); document store encrypted with strict access audit; vendor legs minimise data sent (purpose-bound); impersonation defence on resume tokens; the four-eyes control server-side with both identities audited.`,
    failures: `Verification vendor outage → applications queue at the stage, applicant sees "in review", SLA alerting, policy for extended outage (manual fallback with enhanced review — signed). Screening timeout → the b5 policy (block or provisional per segment). Duplicate submission → business-key dedupe (person+product+day) attaches to existing. Applicant abandons mid-verification → savepoints + expiry with retention-compliant purge.`,
    operations: `Funnel dashboards (drop-off per stage — product gold), stage-SLA alerting, vendor quota utilisation, straight-through rate (the KPI that measures the 1-day promise), four-eyes queue ageing.`,
    migration: `Segment-by-segment cutover from the legacy process (retail simple first); parallel evidence-format validation with compliance before each segment; the legacy process retires per segment with a date.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: orchestration over choreography (human tasks, visibility, audit). ADR-2: risk-tiered straight-through processing (speed with governed exceptions). ADR-3: provisional activation policy as explicit product (conversion vs control, bounded).`,
    followups: ['Corporate onboarding with UBO chains — what changes?', 'The risk model misclassifies a segment — blast radius and rollback?', 'Where does GDPR deletion apply to abandoned applications?'],
    rubric: ['Workflow state explicit and applicant-visible', 'Vendor legs isolated with pacing and policies', 'Risk-tiered approval with governed straight-through', 'Evidence versions on every decision', 'Retention rules for non-customers handled'] },

  { id: 'cs11', title: 'Customer & Partner Screening Platform (flagship)', difficulty: 'Expert', banking: true,
    problem: `The full b5 design as a case study: screen customers AND partners on onboarding, data changes and list updates; vendor matching engine; case management with four-eyes; 10-year evidence; and the sixteen failure scenarios as first-class requirements. Attempt it seriously — this is the interview centrepiece for financial-crime roles.`,
    clarifying: ['Party population and change velocity?', 'Vendor quota and latency SLAs?', 'List types and update cadence (delta support?)', 'Interactive decision budget for onboarding?', 'Which decisions need four-eyes?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** initial + ongoing screening (three triggers), partner scoping via relationships/UBO, vendor integration, hit → case → task workflow, four-eyes release, re-screening (corrections, list deltas), bulk + real-time lanes, operational dashboards.\n**NFR:** interactive p99 ≤ 5 s; no silent drops (compliance control); evidence reconstructible 10 y incl. list + data + logic versions; batch re-screen of 3M parties overnight; hit→case integrity 100% (reconciled).\n**Volumes:** 3M parties, 40k changes/day, weekly list updates (occasional 40k-entry deltas), vendor 100 req/s.`,
    scale: `Interactive load trivial (≈3/s); the sizing exercise is the list-delta re-screen: worst case ~1M affected matches at 80 req/s (bulkheaded batch share) ≈ 3.5 h — fits the overnight window with alerting margin. Evidence store growth ~200 GB/yr — synchronous replication affordable at that size (the RPO-0 scoping decision).`,
    options: `1. Vendor's full suite incl. case management: evidence locked into their exit terms — the one thing you must keep (bx20 reasoning).\n2. Vendor matching engine + owned orchestration/case/evidence: the defensible hybrid.\n3. Build matching in-house on Elasticsearch: owning regulated matching quality without a vendor's amortised validation — priced and rejected (bk60).`,
    recommended: `Option 2, the b5 reference architecture: party/relationship events (inbox-deduped) → **orchestration** (scope computation incl. UBO traversal; requests persisted with outbox; business-key idempotency partyId+trigger+listVersion) → **vendor adapter** (ACL, Resilience4j stack, retry topics — ordering sacrifice acceptable: downstream version checks — durable queue on outage) → results → **case management** (one case per hit via constraint + inbox; four-eyes state machine; ES read model for investigators) → **evidence store** (append-only, sync-replicated, versions of everything). Batch lane: Spring Batch, checkpointed, bulkheaded to 80% of vendor quota with the interactive 20% reserved.`,
    tradeoffs: `The hybrid pays integration cost to keep evidence sovereignty — the deliberate trade. Retry-topic reordering accepted on requests (version-checked downstream) but NOT on the case-decision stream. Pre-computation of screening status for the payments platform (cs9 dependency) accepts a bounded staleness window, compliance-signed, shrunk by list-delta events.`,
    dataApis: `The b5/bx4 entity set: ScreeningRequest/Result/Hit, Case, InvestigationTask, EvidenceRecord(party-version, list-version, logic-version, matches, decision, maker, checker). APIs: interactive screen (onboarding contract), case worklists, evidence retrieval ("all decisions under list v42" — a rehearsed query), admin (list-status, replay) behind PAM.`,
    kafka: `screening.requests/results/hits.v1 as per the [event catalogue](#/kafka-designer) — keys, ACLs (hits restricted!), retention; DLTs with paging (a silent drop is a control failure by definition); consumes customer.events.v1, relationship.events.v1.`,
    security: `Hit data = toxic: minimal consumers, tight ACLs, no fan-out; threat model priorities = tampering with decisions (immutable, versioned) and insider misuse (four-eyes server-side, access-audited evidence store, PAM'd admin plane); vendor data flows purpose-bound.`,
    failures: `All sixteen b5 scenarios addressed; the headline five: missed event (count reconciliation + version full-sync + heartbeat canary), DB-vs-Kafka (outbox), vendor outage (queue + signed business policy), hit-without-case / duplicate-case (constraint + bidirectional reconciliation, orphan hits page compliance), replay duplicates (business-key idempotency, dedupe retention ≥ replay horizon).`,
    operations: `Dashboards: screening backlog age, vendor health, hit→case reconciliation status, list-version currency, four-eyes queue SLAs, batch ETA vs window. Every reconciliation has an owner and a break workflow — they are controls, not charts.`,
    migration: `Strangle the legacy screening tool: new platform shadows (same inputs, compare outcomes) for a quarter — the comparison IS the model-validation evidence for regulators; then trigger-by-trigger cutover (onboarding first, list-driven last); legacy evidence migrated with integrity verification or retained read-only per retention.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: hybrid sourcing (evidence sovereignty). ADR-2: business-key idempotency for requests (replay safety). ADR-3: RPO-0 scoped to evidence store. ADR-4: retry-topic ordering trade on requests only.`,
    followups: ['A regulator asks: prove no party went unscreened last quarter — walk the evidence chain.', 'The vendor doubles their latency SLA — which lane breaks first and what is the lever?', 'Why is the orphan hit worse than the duplicate case?'],
    rubric: ['Capacity maths drove the lane split', 'All three triggers with distinct lanes', 'Idempotency keyed on business facts', 'Evidence model complete (all versions)', 'Failure drills answered with named mechanisms', 'Sourcing trade defended'] }
  ]);
})(window.SAA.data);
